      <p>To simplify the model description in what follows, without loss of generality, let us suppose that the model is run with MNase-seq alone. As described earlier, the two-dimensional MNase-seq data are transformed into two one-dimensional signals (Figure <xref rid="F2" ref-type="fig">2D</xref>); the midpoint counts of <monospace>nucFrags</monospace> primarily influence the learned nucleosome positions and the midpoint counts of <monospace>shortFrags</monospace> primarily influence the learned TF binding sites. In both cases, a negative binomial (<italic toggle="yes">NB</italic>) distribution is used to model the emission probabilities. We use two sets of <italic toggle="yes">NB</italic> distributions to model the midpoint counts of <monospace>nucFrags</monospace>. One distribution, <inline-formula><tex-math id="M18">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
